%%TITLE
The prevalence of human papilloma virus (HPV) infections in oral squamous cell carcinomas: a retrospective analysis of 88 patients and literature overview.
%%ABSTRACT
In addition to tobacco and alcohol consumption, the two main risk factors for oral squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC), recent studies have revealed infections with human papilloma virus (HPV) as an additional risk factor for OSCC development. In the field of head and neck malignancies, the prevalence of HPV infections in oropharyngeal cancer (OC) ranges in different studies up to 84%. While HPV infection is discussed as an independent risk factor in this region, its distinguished role in carcinogenesis of tumours localized to the oral cavity remains still uncertain. In this study, we analysed the HPV status in 88 consecutive patients with OSCCs localized anterior of the palatoglossal arch who were treated in the Department of Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery at the University Medical Center Mainz. The HPV status analysis was performed using DNA-PCR and immunostaining of p16 protein. The prevalence of HPV-positive OSCCs was about 6% (5 patients). In 3 patients the HPV subtypes 16/18 were found. No significant differences between the HPV positive and negative patients regarding age, gender, smoking and alcohol consumption, localization and TNM level could be detected. Contrary to other studies focussing on cancers of the lingual and palatine tonsil, the prevalence of HPV infections was much lower in the oral cavity. Therefore HPV infection might play a less important role in oral carcinogenesis.
%%MATERIAL AND METHODS
Patients collective
All patients (n 88) treated in the Department of Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery, University Medical Center Mainz from December 2011 until June 2013 were included. The only inclusion criterion was a histopathological diagnosis of OSCC located be- tween the lips and the palatoglossal arch, including the tongue, mandible, maxilla and the buccal region. The exclusion criteria were OSCC relapses, any other SCC localization as well as other malignant tumour entities. HPV status, age, gender, tumour local- ization, TNM classiﬁcation, smoking and alcohol consumption were analysed for these patients.
HPV testing and typing
Every time a specimen is taken from a patient to conﬁrm diagnosis for OSCC in our department, an additional test to detect HPV in the specimen is performed by using DNA-PCR and immu- nostaining of the p16 protein at the Institute of Virology, University Medical Center Mainz, in order to optimize the peri-operative therapeutical regime of these patients (e.g., adjuvant radiochemotherapy).
In totally, 88 specimens were taken from 88 patients and sub- sequently frozen at -20 o C until analysis. The samples were each taken in 300 l phosphate-buffered saline (DPBS, no CaCl2 and
MgCl2, pH 7.0e7.3; Gibco, Life Technologies, Darmstadt, Germany)
and homogenized with ceramic balls (2.8 mm; Peqlab Biotech- nology, Erlangen, Germany) in a mixer mill (Retsch MM300; Haan, Germany). 100 l of the homogenate was always added to an equal
volume of digestion buffer (20 mM Tris pH 8.3, 100 mM KCl, 5 mM
MgCl2, 0.2 mg/ml gelatin, 0.9% Tween 20) containing about 3 l of proteinase K (600 U/ml; Thermo Scientiﬁc, Schwerte, Germany). Incubation was done for at least 1 h at 56 oC until the content had
clariﬁed.
Subsequent DNA extraction was performed by the fully auto- mated sample prep system Qiacube (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany) using a Qiagen spin-column kit (QIAmp Min Elute Virus Spin kit).
The elution volume was 100 l. 10 l of the puriﬁed DNA were used for each analysis with the commercially available line probe assay
‘INNO LiPA HPV Genotyping Extra’ (Innogenetics, Gent, Belgium).
This test has been developed for the identiﬁcation of 28 different clinically relevant human papilloma virus genotypes by ampliﬁcation of speciﬁc sequences in the conserved L1 capsid region of the HPV genome using biotinylated SPF 10 primers ( ). Ampliﬁcation was done according to the manufac- turer’s protocol in a GeneAmp 9700 thermocycler (Applied Bio- systems, Life Technologies, Darmstadt, Germany) and the generated biotinylated amplicons were further processed using the Autoblot 3000H system (MedTech Inc., Hillborough, USA). The biotinylated amplicons were denatured and subsequently hybrid- ized with HPV genotype speciﬁc oligonucleotide probes which are immobilised on a nitrocellulose membrane strip. The addition of streptavidin-conjugated alkaline phosphatase and a chromogenic substrate leads to a visually evaluable precipitate at HPV genotype speciﬁc probe lines on the membrane.
As a control for the quality of the sample DNA and the efﬁcient preanalytical DNA extraction procedure, a sequence of the human HLA-DPB1 Gene was co-ampliﬁed and also detected by the LiPA.
Statistical analysis
The deﬁned independent variables were analysed between the two HPV-positive and HPV-negative patient subgroups by using the Student’s t-test (age), the Fisher exact test (gender, smoking and alcohol consumption) and by a Pearson Chi Square test (localiza- tion, TNM stadium). P-values 0.05 were considered to be signiﬁcant.
